extends ../_base

include _meta
include _post

block head
	+post-head('Getting more complaints')

block body
	+post
		+heading('Getting more complaints', 'Maciej Łaszcz', '8 March 2020')

		+section
			+p.
				User complaints, customer gripes, personal grumbles, are very
				beneficial to product's development process. By discovering
				what users find annoying about your product you can easily
				delight them by improving their workflow and fix the product
				in ways that you wouldn't discover on your own.

			+p.
				Complaints don't have a good place in the modern SaaS world -
				there are a lot of great real-time communication tools
				available like Intercom or Drift and even more great email
				support tools, but neither of these channels are optimized for
				gathering complaints as there's way too much friction for users
				to simply point out quick issues they might have with your
				product (detailed reasons why are at the end of this
				article).

			+p
				+a(href="/blog/negative-feedback") Getting a small public lynching of your product 
				.
					is one of the more interesting ways of collecting
					complaints. Unfortunately even though product developers
					could start creating such hate threads on their own
					products I obviously wouldn't encourage it, instead we
					propose a few simple practices that we've learned along
					the way of building 
				+a(href="/") Gripeless 
				| that will help you get more complaints about your product.

		+section
			+h2 Make complaints solicited
			+p.
				The most important decision that a person makes before making a
				complaint is to judge whether the service provider actually
				#[span.italic wants] to receive any complaints.
			+p.
				Because most people by default don't think that service
				providers are open to complaints you can very easily be missing
				out on complaints and potential problems that could lead to the
				person and others churning.

			+p
				.
					Including a small note describing your desires for
					feedback and complaints, how every bit of even the most
					negative feedback is fine, or a message like
				span.italic "We can only fix problems we know about" 
				.
					can go a very long way into making complaints feel
					solicited.

		+section
			+h2 Make complaints easy
			+p.
				The sole fact that someone has to go out of their way and
				make an effort to report issues about an app to a person they
				don't even know can alone also be a big reason why people are
				hesitant to do it.

			+h3 Don't gate complaints behind email
			+p
				.
					Email sets certain expectations on its users that they have to meet - since people sign emails with their real names it would be considered quite rude to just leave a message like 
				span.italic "playlist button broken" 
				.
					even though that's all the complainer really wants to say.
			+quote('- A complainer wasting time on writing boilerplate around a simple message')
				+p "Hey,

				+p.
					Just wanted to report that the playlist save button
					doesn't work some of the time. It breaks my workflow
					quite a bit, hope that it gets fixed soon!

				+p It's nothing big, but just wanted to let you know.

				+p All the best,<br> My name"

			+p.
				All the things that go into a typical email are completely
				unnecessary in the process of complaining, and because they
				exist they could scare away some juicy complaints.

			+h3 Don't gate complaints behind real-time chat
			+p.
				Okay, if writing a full email is too much, why wouldn't users
				just use my real-time chat plugin that I have? They can write
				much less to convey their message and still sound nice, this
				must be a good solution? #[strong Wrong.]
			+p.
				Even though there's less letters involved, the same etiquette
				reasons are maintained in the real time chat. This is because
				both of those channels imply that you're going to have a
				#[strong conversation with a real person].

			+p
				.
					The structure of a complaint doesn't involve a
					conversation - unless asking for more details. Most of
					the time it's simply pointing out something that a person
					disliked. 
				strong.
					People are less likely to admit what they don't like if
					they're in a conversation
				.
					, compared to something like
					submitting an anonymous ballot.

			+quote('- A complainer again wasting time on writing boilerplate around a simple message in real-time chat').
				"Hey [real person representing Company], just wanted to quickly
				report that the playlist save button is broken and it's
				breaking my workflow quite a bit. Nothing major but I hope it
				gets fixed soon! Thanks!"

			+p.
				It's also quite inconvenient for users to point out several
				of the gripes they might have with a product in a single
				message, or multiple messages and their "niceness" must
				increase with each gripe so that they don't seem rude - which
				is completely unnecessary.

			+h3 Do provide a simple complaint channel
			+p.
				Something like a simple text form that you embed on your site
				is a great start to making your product complaint-focused. If
				it's labeled well (use our tips above) it doesn't suffer from
				the same etiquette problems as email or real-time chat
				allowing users to quickly point out everything that they
				dislike without being judged that they're doing so.

			+quote('- A happy complainer that could finally express his problem with almost no effort').
				"playlist save button is broken"

			p Some other ideas include:
			+ul
				li Embedding "anonymous complaint" forms into your email conversatoins with customers
				li Encouraging users to use your simple feedback form from time to time in a way that suits your product

			+p.
				It's important to ensure that any type of feedback is easy to
				send and that it's always welcomed.

		+section
			+h2 Make complaints actionable
			+p.
				You could get every person in the world to complain about your
				product, but the complaints will be useless until you actually
				fix the problems that get pointed out.

			+p.
				While most of the time you won't need to talk to the complainer
				at all, if something is not clear always follow-up to ask for
				more details. The complainer will be delighted that you're
				interested in improving the product specifically for them, and
				it's also a good opportunity to learn more about how they use
				your product.

			+p
				.
					Also, don't get discouraged if you get a lot of negative
					sounding complaints at first (
				+a(href="/blog/negative-feedback") like when your product gets posted to /r/programmingcirclejerk
				.
					) - letting people be mean is
					actually the key to more complaints and in turn, providing
					a better service leading to more revenue.

	+related-posts
		+negative-feedback-preview

	+blog-footer
